      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0646P0-06460'>
        <a name='S5LV0646P0_20030403_GCR_91'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-whitty' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0646P0_20030403_GCR_91' title='Link to this speech by Mr John Whitty' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-john-whitty" title="Mr John Whitty">Lord Whitty</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I ignored the point because it was not particularly relevant to this amendment. The Environment Agency can conceivably be a party to the action only if it has granted a licence for activity that caused the damage. Even then, one would have to show that it had behaved perversely and unreasonably, which is always the case when contemplating action against a public licensing body. That is not relevant to the issue of small abstractors.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0646P0-06461'>
